    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1960-09-03T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1960-09-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="152"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d152">
                <head>152. Circular Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss>
                    to <gloss type="to">Certain Diplomatic Missions</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d152fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 320/9–360. Confidential; Priority. Drafted by Green and <persName
                            corresp="#p_FCVJ1">Ferguson</persName>; cleared by <gloss
                            target="#t_AFN1">AFN</gloss> and in substance by <persName
                            corresp="#p_KFD1">Kohler</persName>; and approved by <persName
                            corresp="#p_PJK1">Penfield</persName> who signed for Herter. Sent to 17
                        posts in Africa. The time of transmission is not legible on the source
                        text.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1960-09-03">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 3, 1960</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>345. Circular 341.<note n="2" xml:id="d152fn2">See <ref target="#d151fn1"
                            >footnote 1</ref>, <hi rend="italic">
                            <ref target="#d152">supra</ref>
                        </hi>.</note> While desiring avoid Soviets’ turning <gloss target="#t_UNGA1"
                        >UNGA</gloss> into worldwide “summit,” Department does not wish put pressure
                    on leaders African states, especially new states, not to attend, so long as this
                    is not result Soviet pressure. Posts in dealing with <gloss target="#t_REFTEL1"
                        >reftel</gloss> should avoid giving such impression and should indicate
                    African chiefs of state, prime ministers, foreign ministers and others will be
                    most welcome in US, although they may wish weigh benefits obtained by attendance
                    on occasion admission their country to <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> against
                    possibility such attendance might be used by Soviets turn session into something
                    highly undesirable from their, as well as our, point of view.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="strong">Herter</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
